  ● Done. Here's what the file does and the key design decisions:

  Sliding window via worker pool

  Instead of a semaphore, N independent async workers share a single pending[] array and each calls .shift() to grab the next chunk. This naturally
   creates a window of exactly N concurrent uploads — as one finishes, it immediately picks up the next. No coordination needed beyond the shared
  queue.

  Race condition on completion

  When the last few chunks are in-flight simultaneously, one chunk triggers server-side completion (rename + session cleanup). Other workers that
  were mid-upload get a 404. The handler treats 404 as 'gone' (session completed by peer) — sets completed = true and exits cleanly, rather than
  throwing an error.

  Pause accuracy

  Pause time is excluded from speed/ETA: pauseStart captures when pause begins, totalPausedMs accumulates each pause duration, and activeMs =
  Date.now() - uploadStartTime - totalPausedMs gives real active wall time. Pause also works during hashing (checks between chunks).

  Resume without rehash

  localStorage stores { upload_id, chunk_size, chunk_hashes }. On "Check & Resume", the client queries GET /fs/upload-session/:id for the server's
  received_chunks[], pre-colours those cells green, and only uploads the missing ones — no rehash.

  Config lockout

  Chunk size and window size selectors are disabled during upload so they can't be changed mid-session (which would invalidate the manifest).


